properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong Pacific frontal system moving across the B.C. South Coast this morning will give potentially damaging winds. For Metro Vancouver, Southern Gulf Islands, Sunshine Coast - Gibsons to Earls Cove and communities in the mouth of Howe Sound, including Bowen Island, the south to southeast winds up to 60 km/h will veer sharply to the northwest 40 to 60 km/h with gusts up to 70 this morning. The winds will abate near noon as the front moves inland. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, and significant snow melt are expected. Total rainfall amount: 40 to 60 mm, possibly higher in areas of heaviest rain. Location: Northwest New Brunswick. Time span: this evening through Wednesday morning. Remarks: A slow moving, intense low pressure system will move into New England today and into southern Quebec on Wednesday. Rain ahead of this system will begin this evening and become heavy at times tonight. Temperatures will also rise to above 10 degrees on Tuesday contributing to significant or total melting of the snow pack. Total rainfall amounts of 40 to 60 mm are expected before rain gradually ends Wednesday morning, however higher amounts are possible if several heavy rain bands move over the same area in succession. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Messy week ahead with periods of snow, freezing rain, and rain expected. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm. Freezing rain duration: 8 to 12 hours. Locations: central Labrador and coastal Labrador from Hopedale and vicinity to Cartwright. Time span: overnight tonight until Thursday afternoon. Remarks: Snow will begin this evening over western Labrador and spread to central and coastal Labrador by Tuesday morning. North of Rigolet, the precipitation is expected to remain as snow through Wednesday. From Rigolet to Cartwright and through Upper Lake Melville and Eagle River the snow will change to rain Tuesday afternoon or evening then to a potentially extended and significant period of freezing rain overnight Tuesday night through Wednesday. Eastern areas of Eagle River and coastal areas of Cartwright to Black Tickle may avoid the freezing rain as temperatures should remain just above freezing. All areas should see the precipitation transition to rain Wednesday night into Thursday. The heaviest snowfall rates are expected during the day on Tuesday and the heaviest freezing rainfall rates are expected overnight Tuesday and into Wednesday morning. This wintry mix of snow, freezing rain and rain is expected to finally end later on Thursday. Snowfall and/or Freezing Rain Warnings might be needed for some areas in subsequent forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:
Description: A long episode of heavy rain is expected. Maximum rainfall amounts: 80 to 130 mm, except possibly exceeding 150 mm in the extreme southwestern region of the province. Locations: most of southwestern and central New Brunswick. Time span: this evening through Wednesday morning. Remarks: A slow moving, intense low pressure system will move into New England later today and into Quebec on Wednesday. This system will pump frequent periods of heavy rain into the province beginning this evening and continuing on Tuesday before easing off Wednesday morning or early afternoon. At this time, rainfall amounts are expected to be heaviest in the southwestern portion of the province where rainfall amounts of 80 to 130 mm are possible by late Tuesday with additional amounts expected on Tuesday night and into Wednesday, potentially giving total rainfall in excess of 150 mm in some areas before ending on Wednesday. Similar rainfall events in the past have caused road washouts and localized flooding in low-lying areas. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
